thread_title: Who's gone back to classic rubbers after Tensors/Tenergy?
reply_split: Blocking is easier with Mark V than with Aurus Soft – obviously, opponents differ in how much kick they can put on their loops, but against some people, I feel I could just block reliably all day with Mark V. Unsure about how much different service spin generation is – I like to throw in some backhand swipe serves with heavy sidespin, and my vague feeling is that it takes a little more elbow grease with the Mark V.When I come off Mark V next year, I'll probably go back to Aurus Soft, or maybe back to Victas V-15 Limber, whose soft, slow feel I didn't like before; but which might be a good compromise between the control of Mark V and the relatively greater catapult of Aurus Soft.
reply_sub: Blocking is easier with Yasaka-Mark-V than with Tibhar-Aurus-Soft – obviously, opponents differ in how much kick they can put on their loops, but against some people, I feel I could just block reliably all day with Yasaka-Mark-V. Unsure about how much different service spin generation is – I like to throw in some backhand swipe serves with heavy sidespin, and my vague feeling is that it takes a little more elbow grease with the Yasaka-Mark-V.When I come off Yasaka-Mark-V next year, I'll probably go back to Tibhar-Aurus-Soft, or maybe back to Victas V-15 Limber, whose soft, slow feel I didn't like before; but which might be a good compromise between the control of Yasaka-Mark-V and the relatively greater catapult of Tibhar-Aurus-Soft.

thread_title: Which Euro/Jap rubber beats Tenergy for pushing/serving?
reply_split: As I get to return serves all the time from all the top players at our association, the spinniest serves and pushes would come from our Chinese ex-provincial members who use DHS H3 or Haifu Whale... Definitely heavier in spin than T05, perhaps by about 25%... Other non-Chinese rubbers that can produce roughly the same amount of spin as T05 in serves and pushes are Calibra LT, Acuda S1, Stiga Boost TP and Yasaka Rakza 7... Maybe T05 could push heavier than these, but I do not feel it from Zaman M. or Justin N... As a matter of fact I have never felt T05 users could overpower me with extra spin than most other non-Chinese inverted...
reply_sub: As I get to return serves all the time from all the top players at our association, the spinniest serves and pushes would come from our Chinese ex-provincial members who use DHS-Hurricane-3 or Haifu Whale... Definitely heavier in spin than Butterfly-Tenergy-05, perhaps by about Butterfly-Tenergy-25%... Other non-Chinese-rubbers that can produce roughly the same amount of spin as Butterfly-Tenergy-05 in serves and pushes are Stiga-Calibra-LT, Donic-Acuda-S1, Stiga-Boost-TP and Yasaka-Rakza-7... Maybe Butterfly-Tenergy-05 could push heavier than these, but I do not feel it from Zaman M. or Justin N... As a matter of fact I have never felt Butterfly-Tenergy-05 users could overpower me with extra spin than most other non-Chinese inverted...

thread_title: Review of Donic Acuda S1 Turbo and Hexer HD
reply_split: It is about as fast as O4A on fast attacking shots but often much slower on slow and midpower placement shots.Tensor/Catapult: noticeably more pronounced on Acuda.Control: pretty good on both, but better on O4ASpin: better on Acuda for all strokes but fast loopsSensitivity: better (less sensitive) for O4AFlat game: slightly better for O4ALooping: opening loops better for Acuda, counterlooping and fast loopkills - some advantage for O4AShort game: about the same but O4A is a bit more predictable for me, produces less unexpected pushes into the netBackhand game: O4A is better since usually people play more placement shots, pushes and placement shots on BH , and O4A beats Acuda thereI would recommend Acuda over O4A only to the players who are heavily spin-oriented and rarely do "soft" strokes on their FH (except an opening loop).
reply_sub: It is about as fast as O4A on fast attacking shots but often much slower on slow and midpower placement shots.Tensor-rubbers/Catapult: noticeably more pronounced on Donic-Acuda.Control: pretty good on both, but better on O4ASpin: better on Donic-Acuda for all strokes but fast loopsSensitivity: better (less sensitive) for O4AFlat game: slightly better for O4ALooping: opening loops better for Donic-Acuda, counterlooping and fast loopkills - some advantage for O4AShort game: about the same but O4A is a bit more predictable for me, produces less unexpected pushes into the netBackhand game: O4A is better since usually people play more placement shots, pushes and placement shots on BH , and O4A beats Donic-Acuda thereI would recommend Donic-Acuda over O4A only to the players who are heavily spin-oriented and rarely do "soft" strokes on their FH (except an opening loop).

thread_title: Innova, Innova Light and Innova Premium
reply_split: Innova Ultra Light:-definitely very light-a bit slower and with softer sponge than the regular Innova-it's quick, I would rate speed at about Mark V level, not a speed demon-control is very good-in-game spin is somewhat lacking (topsheet doesn't seem to grippy to me)-mechanical spin not amazing-brush-loops work, but I can ussually get double the spin from say a Tackiness CII or Sun.-serves are controlled but not very spinny-one great thing is that is quite immune to incoming spin: easy to hit through chops and heavy loops.-throw is medium-high-hitting is also good-blocking is just ok-this rubber needs to be played on a flexible blade, it's just horrible on stiff blades (might have something to do with bottoming out)The regular Innova is very similar: bit faster and a bit harder sponge, maybe a bit more linear as well.Overall they are good ALL+ rubbers, but nothing amazing.
reply_sub: Stiga-Innova-Ultra-Light:-definitely very light-a bit slower and with softer sponge than the regular Stiga-Innova-it's quick, I would rate speed at about Yasaka-Mark-V level, not a speed demon-control is very good-in-game spin is somewhat lacking (topsheet doesn't seem to grippy to me)-mechanical spin not amazing-brush-loops work, but I can ussually get double the spin from say a Tackiness CII or Galaxy-Sun.-serves are controlled but not very spinny-one great thing is that is quite immune to incoming spin: easy to hit through chops and heavy loops.-throw is medium-high-hitting is also good-blocking is just ok-this rubber needs to be played on a flexible blade, it's just horrible on stiff blades (might have something to do with bottoming out)The regular Stiga-Innova is very similar: bit faster and a bit harder sponge, maybe a bit more linear as well.Overall they are good ALL+ rubbers, but nothing amazing.

thread_title: Reviewing Tibhar Evolution EL-P vs MX-P vs T05
reply_split: i have switched from t05 to mxp couple of years ago and never looked back...it is faster than t05 on the fast swing and slower on pushes and slow balls which means more control...sponge is a little harder, for me that is a big plus, for someone else a minus...trajectory of the ball is lower than t05 which i love...my every spin is going low and fast, and still hitting the table...very hard to block...again, for me a plus, for someone else a minus...top surface is grippier than t05, more like Chinese rubbers, so its better for serving...there is softer and harder sponge variant...harder is mx-s...more like h3 in a european way...even lower trajectory than mx-p, more grippy, little slower...perfect bh rubber for pushing, serving and blocking...for fh little too slow unless you have chinese full powerfull stroke to fully penetrate the hard sponge...than its a killer...also very good for tuning...softer are fxp and elp...for me too soft and lively...these are for ppl that like t64...if you dont have enough power they are better than mxs bcs they will speed up your shots...very good if you are standing little further from the table...because they have higher throw and catapult...all and all, really under appreciated rubbers that need more exposure...ask if you have any more questions...
reply_sub: i have switched from Butterfly-Tenergy-05 to Tibhar-Evolution-MX-P couple of years ago and never looked back...it is faster than Butterfly-Tenergy-05 on the fast swing and slower on pushes and slow balls which means more control...sponge is a little harder, for me that is a big plus, for someone else a minus...trajectory of the ball is lower than Butterfly-Tenergy-05 which i love...my every spin is going low and fast, and still hitting the table...very hard to block...again, for me a plus, for someone else a minus...top surface is grippier than Butterfly-Tenergy-05, more like Chinese-rubbers, so its better for serving...there is softer and harder sponge variant...harder is Tibhar-Evolution-MX-S...more like DHS-Hurricane-3 in a european way...even lower trajectory than Tibhar-Evolution-MX-P, more grippy, little slower...perfect bh rubber for pushing, serving and blocking...for fh little too slow unless you have chinese full powerfull stroke to fully penetrate the hard sponge...than its a killer...also very good for tuning...softer are Tibhar-Evolution-FX-P and Tibhar-Evolution-EL-P...for me too soft and lively...these are for ppl that like Butterfly-Tenergy-64...if you dont have enough power they are better than Tibhar-Evolution-MX-S bcs they will speed up your shots...very good if you are standing little further from the table...because they have higher throw and catapult...all and all, really under appreciated rubbers that need more exposure...ask if you have any more questions...

thread_title: Coppa Jo gold vs Coppa Jo Silver vs F1
reply_split: A wolf in sheep's clothingAt first, this rubber sheet may seem a modest development on the COPPA JO Gold from Jan-Ove Waldner, but as soon as it has been glued to the blade, this "grenade" sets an entirely new benchmark.- COPPA JO PLATIN is definitely the fastest and spiniest rubber in the FORMULA DONIC series with incorporated speed glue effect.- COPPA JO PLATIN develops extreme dynamics when playing slightly off from the table.- The sound and speed glue feeling of the COPPA JO PLATIN are in a class of their own.- The bounce of the ball with the COPPA JO PLATIN is both longer and higher and this improves control and increases speed.- The new top sheet, despite its enormous speed, allows good touch for short balls, spin, serves and returns.- The durability of COPPA JO PLATIN has been improved considerably.COPPA JO PLATIN is superior to its competitors in all important aspects.
reply_sub: A wolf in sheep's clothingAt first, this rubber sheet may seem a modest development on the Donic-Coppa-JO-Gold from Jan-Ove Waldner, but as soon as it has been glued to the blade, this "grenade" sets an entirely new benchmark.- Donic-Coppa-JO-Platin is definitely the fastest and spiniest rubber in the FORMULA DONIC series with incorporated speed glue effect.- Donic-Coppa-JO-Platin develops extreme dynamics when playing slightly off from the table.- The sound and speed glue feeling of the Donic-Coppa-JO-Platin are in a class of their own.- The bounce of the ball with the Donic-Coppa-JO-Platin is both longer and higher and this improves control and increases speed.- The new top sheet, despite its enormous speed, allows good touch for short balls, spin, serves and returns.- The durability of Donic-Coppa-JO-Platin has been improved considerably.Donic-Coppa-JO-Platin is superior to its competitors in all important aspects.

thread_title: Are Tenergy/Dignics rubbers really the best?
reply_split: I like that T05 pushes over the table are flat and spinny and gives you a decent serve return that sometimes causes opponent to net if you push fast enough,bear in mind this is one of the highest/arcing throw rubbers so the best of both worlds,even on my thin flex def blade,+longer lasting than most factory boosted rubbers so the extra cost evens out somewhat in the long runI also tried Dignics 05 and for me was inferior to T05 on all shots,serve return in particular where the ball was way too high and I couldn't find a way with it,maybe I'm too used to the t05 where everything seems to work on autopilot for me.
reply_sub: I like that Butterfly-Tenergy-05 pushes over the table are flat and spinny and gives you a decent serve return that sometimes causes opponent to net if you push fast enough,bear in mind this is one of the highest/arcing throw rubbers so the best of both worlds,even on my thin flex def blade,+longer lasting than most factory boosted rubbers so the extra cost evens out somewhat in the long runI also tried Butterfly-Dignics-05 and for me was inferior to Butterfly-Tenergy-05 on all shots,serve return in particular where the ball was way too high and I couldn't find a way with it,maybe I'm too used to the Butterfly-Tenergy-05 where everything seems to work on autopilot for me.

reply_split: Yeah - put that to the topsheet, not to the sponge.Sponge in G1 is much more durable and it's less thick than in t05 so lives pretty longer than it's topsheet (just my own note) Oil on the topsheet surface for 20 minutes makes it grippier even though topsheet is really thick in G1 and it is really grippy because of mechanics of pretty long pips under it.If you apply oil for more than 20 minutes  - it can ruin the surface and if much more time (like couple of hours), then even can lead to bubbles.

thread_title: New Tenergy 05 HARD is coming out next Friday 28th
reply_split: My review :Glued T05H on zhang jike alc blade both sides , previously i was using the same blade with 2 T0505H surely has more gears than 05 and its more powerful Serves :05H is less spinny on soft balls in general also its less bouncy than 05 , so you have to brush more to get the same level of spin and also you'll need to apply a bit more force to make a long serve than you used to do with the 05 ,however you get used to it soon .After 3 practices, i still feel that 05 produces a bit more spin on serves and it is something noticable.Push, touch game and chop :05H has an advantage here due to being less bouncy and  you feel more confident to place the ball where you want on the table ,spin on pushes is pretty much the same as 05 It requires adjustment ,nothing special though.Chops are more controlled, due to less bounciness and lower arcFlicks :I would say that 05H has a disadvantage here , but only in case you go for a soft spinny banana or FH flick , The less dwell time that 05H offers is not forgiving , you maybe feel that it doesnt grip the ball well or it slips ,however this problem appears more when you are uncertain where exactly to hit the ball or out of position or stretching to reach the ball.
reply_sub: My review :Glued T05H on zhang jike alc blade both sides , previously i was using the same blade with 2 T0505H surely has more gears than Butterfly-Tenergy-05 and its more powerful Serves :05H is less spinny on soft balls in general also its less bouncy than Butterfly-Tenergy-05 , so you have to brush more to get the same level of spin and also you'll need to apply a bit more force to make a long serve than you used to do with the Butterfly-Tenergy-05 ,however you get used to it soon .After 3 practices, i still feel that Butterfly-Tenergy-05 produces a bit more spin on serves and it is something noticable.Push, touch game and chop :05H has an advantage here due to being less bouncy and  you feel more confident to place the ball where you want on the table ,spin on pushes is pretty much the same as Butterfly-Tenergy-05 It requires adjustment ,nothing special though.Chops are more controlled, due to less bounciness and lower arcFlicks :I would say that 05H has a disadvantage here , but only in case you go for a soft spinny banana or FH flick , The less dwell time that 05H offers is not forgiving , you maybe feel that it doesnt grip the ball well or it slips ,however this problem appears more when you are uncertain where exactly to hit the ball or out of position or stretching to reach the ball.
